				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Most effective training for a Young Bard<a name="55134"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 4 04 2:50 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>The best training a bard could have is leveling several other toons the oldfashioned way.
<br />

<br />
My bard is the oldest character I still have, but I only came back to her recently.  I started her long ago, before I knew much about EQ at all.  While I enjoyed her, I didn't fully understand her at all.  Got to level 10 or so and on to a new alt, I think it was druid that time...
<br />

<br />
Anyway, 4 years and several characters later, my understanding of bards is so much better.  After 100's of levels as enchanter, druid, necro, war, whatever you get to learn all the roles available intimately.  You know how every class wants every other class to behave.  You learn the limits of your peers in ways you couldn't even fathom otherwise.  When I came back to bard I was amazed at what I could do because I knew almost instictively how all my effects would work, and then the ability to reliably spit them out effectivly.   I mez better then some enchanters my level, Am more likely not to forget snare then almost any druid nowadays (Did all the good druids retire? There used to be some insane druids)  I pull better then the monks and palys all while keeping haste/whatnot and meleeing, getting manasong and regen on, then running off to get the next mob single.  But then I see some bards my level in gear 100x above mine that can't manage to keep 1 song up while they are off meleeing mezed adds, and I wonder why I'm the only bard that plays like I do.
<br />

<br />
I guess the moral of the story is if your gonna bard please learn everything about EQ that you can.  Only then can you use your powers effectively.  If your doing it right people will be amazed, because the amount of bards out there that aren't worth anything is staggering</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
