			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Most effective training for a Young Bard<a name="56960"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 16 04 3:07 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I spent nearly all of my first 50-odd levels as a bard soloing, save for a level here and there of grouping, or doing guild-groups off and on.  I've done every type of kiting, and haven't had a kiting death in...well, ages.  It's sad, really, I find the endless circling soothing.
<br />

<br />
Anyhoo, from 50-58, I've pretty much grouped for most of it, dungeons mainly, the occasional pick-up group or guild event here and there as well. I now have probably 2 dozen or so people that have me on their friends list to do dungeons; when I log on, I can count on having at least two dungeon offers within 10-15 minutes, if that.  In fact, a sk and cleric husband and wife team and I have formed a nightly dungeon group over the last few weeks; heck, even got them into my guild.
<br />

<br />
What I'm trying to say is you're doing fine, keep up the good work.  People remember players who play their class well, and the role of a bard is to be memorable beyond the norm. Tip your hat, take a bow, and revel in the fact that you're a bard.  And be a bard among bards for pick-up groups: bring 'dots for the clerics, always be willing to pull, and always at least listen to your groups suggestions; sure, you may know better, but if you pretend to listen, they feel better about it.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%">Dalvan de`Valaesh, bard's bard extraordinaire
